segments.text: As you were aware, for your contemporary students, what were the sinful activities?
They drank a little.
Did they smoke?
And if so, what did they smoke?
Well, they drank a little.
Hard liquor and mainly beer.
A lot of beer busts.
You know, I said earlier we didn't drink very much, but we did.
We could get keg beer and beer and take it out and have our barbecues and that kind of thing.
And a number of kids smoked.
I didn't.
But a number of them did, and they smoked cigarettes, tobacco.
Very few pipes.
Some, you never know, they were cigar.
But we didn't know, I didn't know anything about dope or drugs.
Did you even know the vocabulary?
Didn't know anything about that until many years later.
What about chewing tobacco?
There were a few that chewed tobacco, but they weren't very clever.
Let's see.
Core trip?
Describe a core trip.
Well, a core trip was twice a year.
The entire core would go off to a football game.
It was to, back in those days, to Austin, Houston, Dallas, Fort Worth.
So it would be like...
in Fort Worth and Houston one year, and Dallas and Austin the other year.
They have those reversed, but anyway.

And the whole core was, well, of course, we had Saturday classes, so it was a little bit difficult to get to a football game in Dallas for 2 o'clock kickoff on Saturday at noon with Saturday morning classes.
So most of that time, the classes on Saturday morning were either scratched or canceled or whatever.
And I remember one of the petroleum professors saying, it doesn't matter what you do because of a poor trip.
Somebody would leave early if you had a poor trip to have.
So kids would leave.
They'd leave early and get to wherever they wanted.
As we mentioned earlier, a lot of them have to travel by hitchhiking.
So we were trying to get to Dallas for a Saturday afternoon game and a parade Saturday morning before that.
You really need to get up there the night before.
Do you remember the Corps trip your senior year when you were Corps Commander?
I remember very well.
Where?
In Dallas and in Austin.
And where in Dallas did y'all march?
We marched, I remember the streets in Dallas.
Elmer, Maine.
Well, we marched up Maine.
We marched, we formed on the west end down there somewhere, marched east, uphill, going uphill.
Okay, okay.
And I remember getting kidded very much about it because it was cold, sort of a wet-ish day, and we wore white gloves and carried sabers.
And when I came up for eyes right with my saber, came up with my hand, and the saber kept going.
But I caught it on the way down.
And, of course, my whole staff, my staff kidded me about that for a long time.
Anyway, that was Dallas.
And then I remember also in Austin, we marched from south to north
on Congress Avenue.

And as Corps Commander, I had several of us went up, the Commandant and my operations officer, and it seemed like another cadet and another officer, went up ahead of time to Dallas and to Austin, talked with the university officials and mainly the police department for the parade to make sure that everything was
and where the march would be, where we would perform, and where we would call out, and so on.
And that's quite pulling to march up Main Street in Dallas with the police escort ahead of you, pull behind you, and band up behind you.
Were there any incidents of either one?
Well, I'm sure there were some, but we had nothing like what you hear about.
And nobody threw anything?
No, I'm sure there was some, but I don't remember any particular problem.
Describe a typical, your senior year, a typical football weekend.
It began when and extended how long?
Well, I guess this would be typical, semi-typical anyway, at least toward the end.
in my senior year, football games were normally, some of them were at night, early in the season, but most of them would be in the afternoon.
So the date would come down either the night before, in my particular case, from the palace area, and by train.
So I'd be there on the train and get her settled in to wherever she was.
and then there'd be various activities on Saturday morning.
What about Friday night?
Usually they'd come in pretty late.
Was there a Yale practice?
Oh yeah, there would be a midnight Yale practice.
Where was it held?
We had midnight Yale practices in the Grove.
I think that's right.
I remember some Yale practices over on the steps of the OIMC.
Now, did your being at Aggie have anything to do with your meeting this young lady?
Well, it did.
I met her in the spring of my junior year when one particular friend from McKinney and a couple of others of us were walking on a Sunday afternoon over to the MSC and we were
over near the main desk now, where it was sort of a living room area.
And this boy from McKinney said, say, there's a girl from my hometown.
Come on over and have an interview with her.
Turned out it's my now wife, 40 years.
And she had been invited down.
She was still in high school.
She had been invited down by a freshman from McKinney.
for the freshman ball and she had been selected sweetheart of the freshman ball.
So I was impressed and then the next fall we ended up having our first date at the Oklahoma State game up in Douglas.
One thing led to another.
Many years later we got married.
My wife and I have been married 40 years.
We married June 15, 57.
Same date as my wife.
You're kidding.
Really?
Yeah, June 15th.
Ours was in central North Carolina.
Back to the typical, so when did the day, the football day begin for a Corps commander?
Midnight Yelp practice or night before?
Midnight Yelp practice, and so we would, you know,
We'll pick up our dates at mid-morning or something like that and take them for a bite to eat, depending on where they were staying and who they were staying with.
We'll have a noon meal, and then Liz and Bill will talk about how this timing would work.
But the Corps would march in ahead of the football game, so we would have to be in uniform, dressing uniform, and fall out in formation probably around 1 if the game was going to be at 2 o'clock.
and we'd fall out over to the new area and march down Joe Ratt Boulevard to Columbia.
Now did you, was it your task to get her placed in the stadium or did she get there on her own?
I ask that question in ignorance because I don't know.
Well, I'm in ignorance myself right now.
I don't remember how we worked that.
But she would be with you at the game?
She would be sitting with me at the game, yes.
Or standing with you?
Standing, yeah.
Now where did the Corps commander...
Where was the corps commander's place in the stadium?
Well, once we passed into view in the stadium and broke formation and went up in the stands, it was every man and his lady for themselves, although there was a certain seating arrangement by class.
The seniors got the lower seats, the better seats, and ranked sort of behind them, if I remember right, freshman and senior higher.
And then if there was a victory, what happened after a victory?
Well, with the victory, it marched over behind the band to Fish Pond and had a little yell practice.
And the yell leaders were...
The yell leaders were dunked into Fish Pond no matter what the weather, cold or hot or whatever.
And then Saturday night was normally... Saturday night there was normally some entertainment around the campus, some kind of dance or something like that.
And then on Sunday morning, we'd normally go to church.
And depending on when the date, had to either get on a train or a car or a bus or something and get back to where she came from.
Did you and your friends attend worship services here in the campus area?
Yes.
Where did you go?
I was a Lutheran by background, and grew up in a Lutheran church, but it seemed like
I went to Anaheim Methodist Church in Northgate more than any other place here.
Did you feel that denominations meant, were terribly important, or was it to go to church for you and your friends?
To go to church.
I still feel that way.
I'm a Presbyterian now.
Let's see.
Final Review.
Describe Final Review in a few days.
Well, you know, final review is an emotional time, and still is, I think, observing the cadets.
But it's sort of the culmination of four years of being in the Corps together.
And in those four years, you've gotten to be very, very close to a number of people, a number of friends.
And it's also, at that point, see the end of the line for being in the Corps, turning over your positions to the
for the next class, and so it was pretty emotional.
It was in my time.
I remember very well the time to turn over to the next Corps commander.
That was held on what's now called Simpson Drill Field.
Was there any particular guest reviewing officer?
There no doubt was a reviewing officer.
I don't recall now.
I've got pictures at home.
Reach back and describe Bonfire when you were an undergraduate.
How big, where?
Bonfire was held on at that time.
I remember working on it pretty hard.
I don't really remember my freshman year, but I'm sure we did.
I'm sure we turned out to be okay.
I remember working on it with some friends in sophomore year, going out to the cut area and that kind of thing.
My senior year as Corps Commander, I remember not doing much with the physical work, but mainly going around visiting and making sure things were
And it was made of timber.
It wasn't trash, it was timber.
It was timber.
It wasn't anything near what it is today.
It wasn't this uniform deal that they tied all this up.
I don't really know why they do it that way now because it tends to policy.
They just stacked it up there and leaned it against each other.
I'm sure there was some time to keep it up there.
It didn't look like it does today.
Silver Taps.
Silver Taps.
Very impressive ceremony.
I remember I don't remember now particular names when we went
And we were a smaller student body at that time, so it didn't occur that it was off and over.
Now they've got it, I guess, just once a month, no matter how many people you kill.
A very impressive ceremony.
I can't help but be impressed by it, being out there in front of the academic building and all the lights out.
Describe what happened, what it was.
Well, I believe it's 10 o'clock in the evening at Silver Taps.
Before that, people start moving toward the open area on the west side of the academic building.
And at the appointed hour, the lights across the campus go out.
And you have the Ross Volunteers fire whatever their salute is, how many ever guns they fire.
And then there's silver taps played from the top of the academic building.
I believe there were five jigglers in the army, laying the taps, it seemed like, about three different times.
They were very impressive, certainly.
And then everybody, there was no one talking when we were over there, no one talking during the ceremony, and no one talking all the way back until dawn.
Other campuses don't understand that, they don't know.
Aggie Muster, do you remember Muster in your days?
Well, I remember Muster, particularly my senior year,
The campus must have had a part in the program.
And a friend of mine, my deputy corps commander, was a senior class president, so we both spoke frequently.
The main speaker was a governor from Colorado.
His name was Thornburg.
He was held on the north side of the MSC.
Where that overhang is, the MSC has been changed since that time.
There were steps there, and it didn't have that dry window that we had there now.
So that had the speakers standing up on top of those steps, and people singing back and forth.
But the main crowd was just on the ground up front.
It wasn't that large a crowd, I guess, at the time.
What are the factors that build Aggie spirit?
What creates Aggie spirit?
Well, that's a hard thing to describe.
I guess no one really completely understands the tradition.
Kids now, when they come, they've got these traditions.
And whether they realize it or not, these traditions were all, essentially all, the main ones, founded in the military days of this college and founded by the Corps.

and have sort of a military background to them in a lot of ways silver caps we were just talking about obviously all those things uh form part of what's called the vegas spirit the i can understand it back in the days you know when my time when
Most of the people, most of the students on the campus were in the Corps because we lived so closely together.
We knew each other.
We really formed a tremendous bond.
Thank goodness a lot of that's still carrying on by every looks.
I guess that's the basis of the spirit.
As you were preparing to leave the campus with your master's degree, what sort of world did you think you were entering?
What did you think it was going to be like?
Well, I didn't really know.
I had worked, I was going to go into the oil business, and I had worked during the summers for different oil companies, but that was mainly sort of physical work.
I wasn't too sure what I was going to get into in business.
But, of course, I also was going to,
I didn't go into the military service for a couple of years because I had taken my advance contract.
I was in the Air Force.
At that time they were looking for people to go to flight school.

Today it's very hard to get into flight school, but at that time I could have gone and chose not to be a pilot because it would have meant a four-year commitment rather than two years that I've been in the service.
had made up my mind by that time that I wanted to pursue the civilian route in the military, although I liked the military very much.
And when I did serve my two years, I learned a tremendous lot.
Do you want me to carry on?
Yes, please do.
I had had some friends in the Corps a couple years ahead of me that had gone into flight school and that kind of thing.
It just seemed like a long time, too.
take four years if you wanted to pursue a business career or an engineering career.
So I chose to go on the two-year route.
But as I said, for two years I was in the Air Force, so it convinced me that I'd gone the right way.
But even so, I really learned a lot dealing with people and so on when I was in the Air Force.
The clothing department works very closely with the clothing industry, so they've given us a pretty good feel for what it was going to be like.
And I guess I didn't have any
real surprises when I went to work.
I worked for Shell one summer, but when I finished with my master's degree, I decided to go work for what has been called Umbiloy Repair Company.
It's now called Exxon.
And it's strange how you make decisions at that period of your life.
I'm not really sure how I made that decision, except I had worked for Shell that one summer, and I didn't particularly like what I had done.
And I really thought that Shell was too much of an international company.
I wanted to go to work for Humboldt Oil and Refining Company, which was, I thought, a domestic operation.
It was after I went to work for them that I realized that they were owned about 60% or 70% by Standard Oil in New Jersey.
changing into Exxon.
And it was much later that I learned that Shell, oil company U.S., is a domestic operation, even though it's owned by Royal Dutch Shell out of Holloman, England, which is the international operation.
But they let Shell Petroleum run its own business, and it is strictly, pretty well, a domestic company.
But I never had any regrets about the company I chose.
It's a fine company right there.
All right, as you recollect, how well did A&M prepare you for the real world?
I thought they prepared me very, very well.
You know, in my profession, patrolling, engineering, as I mentioned, they went very closely with industry.
So I thought, you know, when I went in, no problem.
I never had any problems with my engineering background or that kind of thing.
although they forced me to go to some training schools for the first year or so after I got out of the Air Force.
I felt like I already had most of that.
So I got two ways, I guess.
But beyond that, in the military and dealing with people and that kind of thing, I felt like we were very, very well prepared.
Last two questions are almost the same question phrased differently.
In conclusion, what did it mean, as you look back on it, what did it mean to you, what has it meant to you in your life that you went to Texas A&M?
Well, in the first place, it changed my life dramatically.
It's hard to say, well, A&M versus had I gone to TU, or Baylor, or Rice, or whatever.
I can't do both.
But first of all, it's just the fact that I got a college education changed my life from what it would have been otherwise.
And thank God for people like Tyler Lee Wynn and so on that were given scholarships at that time.
Although I learned later that you could work your way through too, but I didn't know that at the time.
I met my wife here at A&M, just all kinds of things.
And a number of my lifelong friends I made here at the school.

And I guess beyond all that, just the good training, the good experience, the spirit we were just talking about was also sort of a can-do spirit that's built into you here for whatever reason, however you do it.
I think all that was a tremendous benefit to me.
So, what feelings do you have in your heart for A&M?
Well, I love A&M.

When I retired, I came back here and I was looking for work to do and I was offered a teaching position over in the business school, which I did teach for one semester and realized that I didn't like teaching all that much.
I've since gone
for the university to, in some small way, try to pay them back for what they did for my life.
